<h2>How to choose a VPN server ‚Äî key factors</h2>
<p>Top VPNs now offer thousands of servers across hundreds of locations. The goal isn‚Äôt to connect to any random node ‚Äî it‚Äôs to pick the one that best fits your task. The big four are <strong>ping</strong>, <strong>server load</strong>, <strong>location</strong> and <strong>traffic type</strong>.</p>

<h3>1) Ping and distance</h3>
<p>Ping is the round-trip time for a packet. Lower is better. For gaming and calls aim for 20‚Äì60 ms; for streaming ‚â§ 100 ms. Closer geography usually means lower ping, but ISP routes and protocol choice matter too.</p>

<table class="tiny" style="margin:16px auto;border-collapse:collapse;text-align:center;width:100%;max-width:600px;">
<thead><tr><th>From UK to‚Ä¶</th><th>Typical ping</th><th>Good for</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>UK (city near you)</td><td>15‚Äì35 ms</td><td>gaming, banking</td></tr>
<tr><td>DE / NL</td><td>35‚Äì55 ms</td><td>general use, streaming</td></tr>
<tr><td>PL / FR</td><td>40‚Äì70 ms</td><td>VOD alternatives</td></tr>
<tr><td>USA (East)</td><td>90‚Äì150 ms</td><td>Netflix, Hulu</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h3>2) Load and stability</h3>
<p>Apps show server load as a percentage (e.g., 22%). Prefer less crowded nodes ‚Äî the gap between 20% and 70% can translate to 30%+ more throughput. Evenings/weekends: test a couple of nearby regions to avoid spikes.</p>

<h3>3) Traffic type: UDP vs TCP vs IKEv2</h3>
<p><strong>UDP</strong> (WireGuard/NordLynx) is fastest but may drop packets on weak Wi-Fi. <strong>TCP</strong> is steadier ‚Äî good for remote work, banking or buffered streaming. <strong>IKEv2</strong> excels on mobile as it survives network switches (4G ‚áÑ Wi-Fi). If stability is poor, switch protocol and re-check ping.</p>

<h3>4) Encryption & IPv6</h3>
<p>Modern protocols use AES-256-GCM or ChaCha20 ‚Äî ‚Äústronger‚Äù encryption won‚Äôt speed you up. What matters: proper IPv6 handling to avoid leaks. Run a quick check on our <a href="/en-gb/blog/vpn-dns-leak-uk.html">DNS/IPv6 leak test</a>.</p>

<h2>Which country for which goal?</h2>
<p><strong>Streaming:</strong> Netflix/Prime ‚Äî USA or UK. BBC iPlayer ‚Äî UK. TVP Player/Canal+ ‚Äî Poland.<br>
<strong>Torrents (P2P):</strong> look for ‚ÄúP2P friendly‚Äù countries (NL, CH).<br>
<strong>Gaming:</strong> UK/DE/NL ‚Äî closest to the game server.<br>
<strong>Remote work & banking:</strong> your company/bank‚Äôs jurisdiction, often the UK.<br>
See also: <a href="/en-gb/blog/vpn-server-types-uk.html">types of VPN servers</a>.</p>

<h2>Special server types ‚Äî when to use them</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Streaming:</strong> tuned for VOD like Netflix, BBC, Disney+.</li>
  <li><strong>P2P:</strong> better routing, no blocked ports.</li>
  <li><strong>Obfuscated:</strong> hides VPN traffic where ISPs block tunnelling.</li>
  <li><strong>Double VPN:</strong> two-hop chain for extra anonymity (slower).</li>
  <li><strong>Dedicated IP:</strong> stable address for logins and fewer CAPTCHAs.</li>
</ul>

<div class="tip">
<strong>Tip:</strong> server type ‚â† protocol. If speeds drop, try another node or switch protocol.
Details in <a href="/en-gb/blog/vpn-protocols-uk.html">VPN protocols</a>.
</div>

<h2>How to verify a server is ‚Äúgood‚Äù</h2>
<ol>
  <li>Check ping and live load in the app.</li>
  <li>Run a <a href="/en-gb/blog/vpn-speed-test-uk.html">VPN speed test</a>.</li>
  <li>Open your target app (VOD/game) and judge real-world smoothness.</li>
  <li>For P2P, compare transfer rates across 2‚Äì3 nodes in the same region.</li>
  <li>For work, if security systems flag logins, use a <em>Dedicated IP</em>.</li>
</ol>

